	schematypens="http://purl.oclc.org/dsdl/schematron"?><TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><teiHeader><fileDesc><titleStmt><title>Poem 6 (J 281: 1861/1935)</title><author>Emily Dickinson</author></titleStmt><publicationStmt><p>Fascicle 16: Dickinson's variants and published versions</p></publicationStmt><sourceDesc><msDesc><msIdentifier><repository/><idno>1606</idno></msIdentifier></msDesc><bibl><ref target="http://www.cs.virginia.edu/~ajf2j/emily/"/></bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc></teiHeader><text><front><div type="references"><listRef><ptr target="xml/1606variant.xml"/><ptr target="img/1606/fs1606a.jpg"/><ptr target="img/1606/fs1606b.jpg"/><ptr target="img/1606/1606fha.jpg"/><ptr target="img/1606/1606fhb.jpg"/><ptr target="img/1606/1606fhMap.jpg"/><ptr target="img/1606/fs1606Map.jpg"/></listRef></div><div type="witness"><listWit><witness xml:id="df16"><bibl><title>ORIGINAL POEMS</title><author>Emily Dickinson</author></bibl></witness><witness xml:id="fh"><bibl><title>Final Harvest: Emily Dickinson's Poems</title><author>Emily Dickinson</author><editor>Thomas H. Johnson</editor><pubPlace>Boston</pubPlace><publisher>Little, Brown and Company</publisher><date>1961</date></bibl></witness></listWit></div></front><body><head><title>Poem 6 (J 281: 1861/1935)</title></head><lg><l n="1">'Tis so appalling—it exhilarates—</l><l n="2">So over Horror,
               <app><rdg wit="var0 #fh #df16">it half Captivates—</rdg><rdg wit="var1 #df16">it dumb fascinates—</rdg></app></l><l n="3">The Soul stares after it, secure—</l><l n="4"><app><rdg wit="var0 #df16">To know the worst, leaves no dread more—</rdg><rdg wit="var1 #fh #df16">A Sepulchre, fears frost, no more—</rdg></app></l></lg><lg><l n="5">To scan a Ghost, is faint—</l><l n="6"><app><rdg wit="#df16">But grappling, Conquers it—</rdg><rdg wit="#fh">But grappling, conquers it—</rdg></app></l><l n="7"><app><rdg wit="#df16">How Easy Torment, now—</rdg><rdg wit="#fh">How easy, Torment, now—</rdg></app></l><l n="8">Suspense kept sawing so—</l></lg><lg><l n="9">The Truth, is Bald, and Cold—</l><l n="10">But that will hold—</l><l n="11">If any are not sure—</l><l n="12">We show them—prayer—</l><l n="13">But we, who know,</l><l n="14">Stop hoping, now—</l></lg><lg><l n="15">Looking at Death, is Dying—</l><l n="16">Just let go the Breath—</l><l n="17">And not the pillow at your Cheek</l><l n="18">So Slumbereth—</l></lg><lg><l n="19">Others, Can wrestle—</l><l n="20">Yours, is done—</l><l n="21">And so of Woe, bleak dreaded—come,</l><l n="22">It sets the Fright at liberty—</l><l n="23">And Terror's free—</l><l n="24">Gay, Ghastly, Holiday!</l></lg></body></text></TEI>